On every [[Riemannian domain|Riemannian domain]] $$M,$$ there is a unique [[endomorphism field|Endomorphism field]] $$J$$ such that

* $$J^* = -J,$$
* $$J^2 = -I,$$
* $$(X,JX)$$ is positively oriented for all $$0 \ne X \in \T_p M.$$

The [[two-form|Differential form]] $$\det(X,Y) \coloneqq \lang JX,Y \rang$$ is called the //area form// of a Riemannian domain $$M.$$ It is also denoted by $$\d A.$$

* $$J$$ is the positive 90&deg;-rotation with respect to the Riemannian metric.
* <div>In terms of the coordinate vector fields, $$J$$ is given by
$$
JZ = \frac{
  \lang U,Z\rang V - \lang V,Z\rang U
}{
  \sqrt{\lang U,U\rang \lang V,V\rang - \lang U,V\rang^2}
}.
$$
We can construct an orthonormal frame by $$(U/|U|,JU/|U|).$$</div>

* $$\det$$ is the unique two-form such that $$\det(X,Y) = 1$$ for every positively oriented orthonormal basis $$(X,Y)$$ of any $$\T_p M.$$ Note that the orientation of $$(X,Y)$$ is inherited from $$\R^2$$ and independent of the metric.
* $$\lang X,Z \rang Y - \lang Y,Z \rang X = \det(X,Y) JZ.$$
